The modified model is:

$$
\begin{aligned}
lwage_i &= \beta_0
+ \beta_1 belavg_i
+ \beta_2 abvavg_i
+ \beta_3 female_i
+ \beta_4 educ_i \\
&\quad + \beta_5 exper_i
+ \beta_6 expersq_i
+ \beta_7 (female_i \times belavg_i) \\
&\quad + \beta_8 (female_i \times abvavg_i)
+ \beta_9 (female_i \times educ_i) \\
&\quad + \beta_{10} (female_i \times exper_i)
+ \beta_{11} (female_i \times expersq_i)
+ u_i
\end{aligned}
$$
..................

model2=smf.ols('lwage~belavg+abvavg+female+educ+exper+expersq+female*belavg+female*abvavg+female*educ+female*exper+female*expersq',data=beauty).fit(cov_type='HC3')
print(model2.summary())

.....................
hypothesis = """
female:belavg = 0,
female:abvavg = 0,
female:educ = 0,
female:exper = 0,
female:expersq = 0
"""
print("F-test for joint Significance of Interaction Terms:\n")
model2.f_test(hypothesis)
..........................
Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis that the interaction terms are jointly zero. This indicates that the relationship between wages and the explanatory variables differs between males and females.

Since our model was estimated with HC3 heteroskedasticity-robust covariance, this F-test is already heteroskedasticity robust.

So the conclusion is:

-- Using the heteroskodasticity-robust version does not change the qualitative conclusion. The interaction terms remain jointly significant.


